s": "High yield up to 21.39 kg per tree, matures first week of May, early season", "growing_notes": "One of most popular commercially cultivated varieties in India, particularly Punjab and Bihar. LOW-CHILL variety specifically suited to subtropical regions like Jammu and Punjab. Can tolerate transportation. Good for canning. Indigenous to Indian conditions. Regular yield of 70kg/tree. Available as grafted plants.", "availability": "Punjab Agricultural University, Indian nurseries, Ixora Farming, agricultural extension services Kerala", "sort_order": 0}, {"name": "Prabhat (Saharanpur Prabhat) 🌏", "slug": "prabhat-saharanpur-prabhat", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Saharanpur, India - local selection for subtropical plains", "traits": "Medium fruit, attractive appearance", "flesh_fruit": "Good flesh quality, richest source of riboflavin (15.43 μg/g) and thiamine (3.42 μg/g), good niacin content", "yield_notes": "Average yield 64 kg per tree, matures third week of April, early season", "growing_notes": "Popular variety throughout India. Low-chill selection suitable for subtropical areas. Excellent nutritional profile makes it valuable for fresh consumption. Grown in Jammu & Kashmir, low hills and plains. High vitamin content.", "availability": "Indian agricultural universities, northern India nurseries, potentially Kerala agricultural departments", "sort_order": 1}, {"name": "Pratap (Partap) 🌏", "slug": "pratap-partap", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Punjab/North India - widely cultivated local variety", "traits": "Yellow colored with red blush, attractive fruit", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, better firmness compared to others, good riboflavin content (13.53 μg/g)", "yield_notes": "High yield potential - up to 17 kg per tree under favorable conditions, average 70 kg/plant, matures third week of April", "growing_notes": "One of highest yielding varieties in India. Maturity reaches in 76 days from full bloom. Often grown as grafted plant to enhance characteristics. Noted for its high yield reports. Found in Punjab and North India. Early bearer - harvesting by end of April.", "availability": "Punjab nurseries, North Indian agricultural stations, Indian mail-order nurseries", "sort_order": 2}, {"name": "Flordaprince (Florida Prince)", "slug": "flordaprince-florida-prince", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "University of Florida 1982, introduced to India PAU Ludhiana 1968", "traits": "Large attractive fruit, 80% red blush over yellow, firm semi-clingstone", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow melting flesh, highly aromatic flavor, excellent taste, good for fresh consumption", "yield_notes": "Very productive, 150 chill hours, average yield 100kg per tree, matures fourth week of April", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "", "sort_order": 3}, {"name": "Flordasun", "slug": "flordasun", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "University of Florida, introduced to India", "traits": "Medium round fruit, firm skin, good blush", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, semi-clingstone, very firm, excellent flavor", "yield_notes": "Earliest fruiting peach, 150 chill hours, 81 days from bloom, popular variety", "growing_notes": "Successfully grown in India''s subtropical regions. Popular in low hills, plains, and Punjab. Earliest harvest of season. Selected from extensive Florida breeding programs. Widely available in Indian nursery systems.", "availability": "Indian agricultural nurseries, Punjab sources", "sort_order": 4}, {"name": "Earligrande", "slug": "earligrande", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Developed for Indian subtropics", "traits": "Large fruit with excellent color, highest pulp:stone ratio (6.38) with 79.40g pulp weight", "flesh_fruit": "Good flesh quality, maximum TSS (18.86°B), lowest acidity (0.18%), highest total sugar content", "yield_notes": "40% more yield than Shan-i-Punjab, average 95 kg per tree, 73 days from full bloom, early bearer", "growing_notes": "Proved superior to Shan-i-Punjab in trials. Fruits mature slightly earlier. Can be transported to distant markets. Similar disease resistance to Flordasun. Developed specifically for subtropical India. Best pulp to stone ratio of tested varieties. Ideal for fresh consumption due to sweetness.", "availability": "ICAR research stations, Indian horticultural centers", "sort_order": 5}, {"name": "Sharbati 🌏", "slug": "sharbati", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "India - local selection, traditional variety", "traits": "Large fruit, greenish-yellow colored with rosy patches", "flesh_fruit": "Very juicy, nice flavored, rich in antioxidant phenolic compounds, good ascorbic acid (330 μg/g), good riboflavin and thiamine content", "yield_notes": "Average yield 100-120 kg per tree, fruits ripen June-end to first week of July, late season", "growing_notes": "Local Indian variety grown in Punjab, plains areas. One of highest yielding traditional varieties. Later ripening extends season. Distinctly significant cultivar for antioxidants. Ideal for fresh consumption. Traditional Indian selection with cultural significance.", "availability": "Punjab nurseries, northern India agricultural sources", "sort_order": 6}, {"name": "Sharbati Surkha 🌏", "slug": "sharbati-surkha", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "India - Sharbati selection", "traits": "Red-fleshed selection of Sharbati", "flesh_fruit": "Good flesh quality, distinctly significant for antioxidant phenolic compounds, rich in ascorbic acid (310 μg/g), stands out for flavor-imparting organic acids", "yield_notes": "Good producer, used in hybridization programs", "growing_notes": "Best overall cultivar - contains all three groups of nutraceuticals in sufficient amounts for per capita nutrition. Used as female parent in breeding programs. Distinctly significant for phenolic compounds and vitamins. Ideal for fresh consumption and nutritional benefits.", "availability": "ICAR research institutes, specialized Indian nurseries", "sort_order": 7}, {"name": "Pant Peach-1 🌏", "slug": "pant-peach-1", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "G.B. Pant University, Pantnagar, Uttarakhand, India", "traits": "Developed for Indian conditions", "flesh_fruit": "Rich in ascorbic acid (300 μg/g), good niacin content (27.23 μg/g), stands out for organic acids giving excellent flavor", "yield_notes": "Good producer from university breeding", "growing_notes": "Developed by prestigious G.B. Pant University breeding program specifically for Indian growing conditions. Rich source of immune-enhancing vitamins. Similar to Pratap for organic acid content. Modern Indian breeding achievement.", "availability": "G.B. Pant University, Uttarakhand horticultural departments", "sort_order": 8}, {"name": "Khurmani 🌏", "slug": "khurmani", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "India - local traditional variety, grown in Punjab", "traits": "Large attractive fruit with red coloration", "flesh_fruit": "White soft juicy flesh, clingstone", "yield_notes": "Good producer in Punjab region", "growing_notes": "Traditional variety grown in Punjab and northern regions. White-fleshed clingstone type. Local selection adapted to Indian subtropical conditions. Part of traditional Indian peach heritage.", "availability": "Punjab local nurseries, traditional sources", "sort_order": 9}, {"name": "Red June", "slug": "red-june", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Early-season variety introduced to India", "traits": "Medium to large (2.5 inches diameter), vibrant red skin", "flesh_fruit": "Firm, juicy, sweet flesh with good balance of sugar and acidity", "yield_notes": "Early season ripening, good producer", "growing_notes": "Known for vibrant red skin and sweet juicy flesh. Early-season variety valuable for Indian market. Good sugar-acid balance. Grown in various parts of India.", "availability": "Indian commercial nurseries", "sort_order": 10}, {"name": "Florida Red (Flordared)", "slug": "florida-red-flordared", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "University of Florida, introduced to north Indian plains", "traits": "Large fruit, almost red at maturity, attractive appearance", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, freestone, juicy, excellent mid-season fruit", "yield_notes": "Average yield 100 kg per tree, matures early June", "growing_notes": "Low-chill cultivar successfully introduced to north-Indian plains. Used as male parent in Indian hybridization programs. Mid-season variety extends harvest window. Good yields and quality fruit.", "availability": "Northern India agricultural stations", "sort_order": 11}, {"name": "Punjab Red (Nectarine) 🌏", "slug": "punjab-red-nectarine", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Punjab, India - local nectarine selection", "traits": "Smooth skin nectarine, vigorous spreading growth, minimum stone weight (13.96g) giving 57.33g pulp", "flesh_fruit": "Smooth nectarine flesh, highest ascorbic acid (164.33 mg/kg), good flavor", "yield_notes": "Highest yield 23.5 kg per tree, matures second week of May, early bearer - late April/May harvest", "growing_notes": "Best performer in northern hill zone Chhattisgarh trials. Nectarine variation (smooth skin). Extremely high vitamin C content. Early bearing cultivar. Indigenous to Punjab region. Red variety grown commercially.", "availability": "Punjab nurseries, agricultural universities", "sort_order": 12}, {"name": "TropicBeauty", "slug": "tropicbeauty", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "University of Florida & Texas A&M, 1989", "traits": "Round firm fruit, high red overcolor on bright yellow, very short fuzz", "flesh_fruit": "Deep yellow melting flesh, semi-freestone, excellent sweetness", "yield_notes": "150 chill hours, holds well on tree, highly productive", "growing_notes": "Industry standard for subtropical/tropical highlands. Evaluated successfully in Puerto Rico and south Florida. Could potentially work in Kerala hill stations with proper site selection. Parent line used in Taiwan subtropical breeding program.", "availability": "Would need import through agricultural research channels", "sort_order": 13}, {"name": "TropicSnow", "slug": "tropicsnow", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "University of Florida & Texas A&M, 1989", "traits": "40-50% red blush over creamy white background", "flesh_fruit": "White melting flesh, semi-freestone, very low acid with excellent sweetness", "yield_notes": "Good yields, 90-97 day FDP", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "", "sort_order": 14}, {"name": "UFSun", "slug": "ufsun", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "University of Florida", "traits": "Medium-sized, uniformly symmetrical, 50-60% red with darker red stripes", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, clingstone, sweet, sweetens longer on tree", "yield_notes": "Heavy annual crops, ultra-low 150 chill hours, FDP 80 days", "growing_notes": "Ultra-low chill makes it candidate for tropical trials. Non-melting flesh gives good shelf life. Proven in south Florida. Could be tested in Kerala conditions.", "availability": "Would require research import", "sort_order": 15}, {"name": "Tainung No. 7 HongLing", "slug": "tainung-no-7-hongling", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Taiwan Agricultural Research Institute (TARI), released 2020s, subtropical monsoon breeding", "traits": "Large fruit size, attractive appearance, bred specifically for subtropical monsoon climate", "flesh_fruit": "Low acidity characteristic, sweet flavor preferred for fresh consumption", "yield_notes": "Early flowering and harvesting, extremely low chilling requirement", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "", "sort_order": 16}, {"name": "Indian Blood (Cherokee Blood Cling)", "slug": "indian-blood-cherokee-blood-cling", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "China (pre-11th century), brought to Mexico by Spanish 1500s, cultivated by Cherokee and Creek Native American tribes by 1600s. Despite name, not indigenous to India.", "traits": "Large fruit (up to 25cm diameter), dark crimson/scarlet red skin like beet, distinctive appearance", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh with red streaks reaching to stone, crimson just below skin, clingstone, sweet when ripe with tart undertones, distinctive flavor unlike most peaches", "yield_notes": "High yield, very productive, late season (August), dependable", "growing_notes": "One of oldest heirloom peaches brought to Americas. Grown by Thomas Jefferson at Monticello (planted 1807), one of 38 types still at Monticello. Superior canning peach. Grows easily from seed (rare for peaches). Hardy and disease resistant. Rich in anthocyanins (antioxidants). Historical significance - first peaches Spanish missionaries brought to New World. Fragile when ripe. Self-fertile but needs pollinator (not self-fruitful). Pickles beautifully. Used in breeding programs. Medium-high chill requirement (500+ hours) - NOT suitable for Kerala tropical climate.", "availability": "Trees of Antiquity USA, Monticello historic collection", "sort_order": 17}, {"name": "Elberta", "slug": "elberta", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Georgia USA, developed by Samuel H. Rumph, 1875, named for his wife Clara Elberta Moore Rumph, possibly Chinese Cling seedling", "traits": "Large round fruit, golden-yellow skin with crimson blush, attractive appearance", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, freestone, sweet with delicate flavor, firm texture", "yield_notes": "Exceedingly prolific - one small tree can produce 200 peaches, larger trees more, hardy", "growing_notes": "''QUEEN OF PEACHES'' before Redhaven developed. Most important commercial peach 1875-1940s. Revolutionary for shipping - first peach firm enough for long-distance transport un-iced (trial shipment NY 1875). Adapted to all soils and climates Gulf to Great Lakes, Atlantic to Pacific. Foundation of Georgia peach industry and Michigan''s 1890s industry. Still grown commercially. Poem written about it by Mabel Swartz Withoft 1900s. Historical significance - transformed American peach industry. Requires thinning. Late August/September harvest (California July-August). 600+ chill hours - NOT suitable for Kerala.", "availability": "Stark Bros, Grandpa''s Orchard, Trees of Antiquity, heritage nurseries worldwide", "sort_order": 18}, {"name": "Belle of Georgia (Georgia Belle)", "slug": "belle-of-georgia-georgia-belle", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Marshallville Georgia, discovered by Lewis A. Rumph (Samuel Rumph''s uncle), 1870, named for Mrs. Belle Hall, possibly Chinese Cling seedling", "traits": "Large fruit, greenish-yellow skin, creamy white flesh", "flesh_fruit": "White flesh, freestone, firm texture with honeyed sweetness, ''so juicy bathtub good place to eat one'' (1949), excellent flavor", "yield_notes": "Heavy producer, made it prominent peach by end of 19th century", "growing_notes": "Joined Elberta as most popular cultivars of era, remained popular for decades. Commercial growers stopped due to bruising easily despite superior flavor. One of best tasting peaches but unavailable commercially due to delicate nature. White-fleshed with lots of red, sweet honey flavor with acid twist. Excellent winter hardiness and bacterial spot resistance. Historically important to Georgia industry. 600+ chill hours - NOT suitable Kerala. Difficult to find now.", "availability": "One Green World, Trees of Antiquity (limited), heritage collections", "sort_order": 19}, {"name": "Redhaven", "slug": "redhaven", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Michigan State University, developed by Dr. Stanley Johnston, released 1940, revolutionized eastern peach growing", "traits": "Round medium-sized fruit, red skin, attractive appearance", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, freestone, sweet flavor, firm texture", "yield_notes": "Very productive, hardy variety, good bacterial spot resistance", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "", "sort_order": 20}, {"name": "Hiley Belle (Hiley)", "slug": "hiley-belle-hiley", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Marshallville Georgia, introduced by Eugene Hiley, 1886", "traits": "White-fleshed peach with golden skin and red blush", "flesh_fruit": "White flesh, good flavor", "yield_notes": "Good producer", "growing_notes": "Heavily planted throughout middle Georgia for several decades alongside Elberta and Belle of Georgia. Part of trio that defined Georgia peach industry late 1800s-early 1900s. Historical importance to American peach culture.", "availability": "Heritage collections, rare", "sort_order": 21}, {"name": "Carman", "slug": "carman", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Historical variety, once favorite of Midwestern and Southern growers", "traits": "White peach, very rare heirloom", "flesh_fruit": "White flesh, bursting with sweetness, melts in mouth", "yield_notes": "Vigorous and productive", "growing_notes": "Extremely rare heirloom that shouldn''t be lost. Grown as ''El Dulce'' in southern California. Every bit as vigorous/productive now as historically. Once favorite white peach of era.", "availability": "Arboreum Company (currently sold out), extremely rare", "sort_order": 22}, {"name": "J.H. Hale", "slug": "j-h-hale", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "First fruit tree to receive plant patent, famous historical variety", "traits": "Large fruit", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, excellent quality", "yield_notes": "Good producer BUT not self-fertile - requires pollinator", "growing_notes": "Historical significance - first plant patent. Only variety that is NOT self-fruitful - must have another variety to pollinate. Important in peach breeding history.", "availability": "Grandpa''s Orchard, heritage nurseries", "sort_order": 23}, {"name": "Red Rareripe (Morris Red Rareripe)", "slug": "red-rareripe-morris-red-rareripe", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Old heirloom, likely grown by Thomas Jefferson at Monticello, multiple named selections (Prince''s, Martin''s, Pratt, Late Red)", "traits": "Small fruit (not surpassing 3.5 inches diameter), red blush sometimes on and under skin", "flesh_fruit": "Described as productive, melting, highly flavored, excellent, superior to supermarket varieties", "yield_notes": "Productive", "growing_notes": "Near-wild variety, grows true from seed (unique for peaches). Hardier than most peaches - survives Zone 5A. Early ripening historically, though ripens September in northern climates. Yellow and white varieties existed (''lemon rareripes''). Grows easily from pits with cold stratification. More tedious to process due to small size but superior flavor. Jefferson recommended 20ft apart for great production and firewood. Hundreds of seedlings possible from dropped fruit.", "availability": "Rare, mainly through seed savers, some heritage collections", "sort_order": 24}, {"name": "Cresthaven", "slug": "cresthaven", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Michigan State University, Dr. Stanley Johnston, released few years after Redhaven 1940s", "traits": "Developed for cold climates", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, freestone, excellent flavor", "yield_notes": "Good yields, cold hardy", "growing_notes": "Follow-up to Redhaven success. Another heirloom peach from famous ''Haven'' breeding program. Cold climate adaptation. Part of revolution in northern peach growing.", "availability": "Heritage nurseries, cold-climate specialists", "sort_order": 25}, {"name": "Golden Jubilee", "slug": "golden-jubilee", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Bred from Elberta, real heirloom variety", "traits": "Large late yellow peach", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, sweet rich flavor, good texture", "yield_notes": "Self-fertile, low-chill variety", "growing_notes": "Works well in South. Might be best variety for California and similar climates. Showy pink spring blossoms add ornamental value. Descended from famous Elberta.", "availability": "Arbor Day Foundation, heritage nurseries", "sort_order": 26}, {"name": "Loring", "slug": "loring", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Missouri peach, 1950s+, grown across country", "traits": "Large fruit, pink spring blossoms", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, good for desserts and canning", "yield_notes": "Good producer, pretty adaptable", "growing_notes": "Sold at orchards in 1990s. Adaptable across country. Ornamental features with edible fruit perfect for edible gardens. Heirloom peach with wide geographic success.", "availability": "Heritage nurseries, Bennett Orchards", "sort_order": 27}, {"name": "Dixieland", "slug": "dixieland", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "USDA introduction to fill void when Elberta passion waned", "traits": "Large fruit, yellow skin with red blush", "flesh_fruit": "White flesh, sweet soft flesh", "yield_notes": "Good producer", "growing_notes": "Excellent for fresh eating or baking. Introduced to maintain peach industry when Elberta popularity declined. White-fleshed heirloom from USDA breeding.", "availability": "Heritage collections", "sort_order": 28}], "variety_count": 49}'::jsonb,
  variety_count = 49, status = 'parsed'
WHERE source_path = 'brainstorm-inbox/import-payloads/peach.json';

